{"cursor":"21682","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n'Sousveillance' ( ; ) refers to the recording of an activity by a participant in\nthe activity [http://www.surveillance-and-\nsociety.org/articles1(3)/sousveillance.pdf \"Sousveillance: Inventing and Using\nWearable Computing Devices...]\", by Steve Mann, Jason Nolan and Barry Wellman,\nin Surveillance & Society 1(3), 2003 \"Sousveillance: Inverse Surveillance in Multimedia Imaging'', by Steve\nMann, in ACM Multimedia 2004, pp. 620â627 \"Keeping a Close Watch\", by\nKingsley Dennis, Sociology Department, Lancaster University, Lancaster, UK, 2008\nJuly 30th, in The Sociological\nReview [http://wearcam.org/metalandflesh.htm Sousveillance, not just\nsurveillance, in response to terrorism], 2002 March 1st, Metal and Flesh, Volume\n6, No. 1 typically by way of small wearable or portable personal\ntechnologies. Vol. 31, Issue 2 â April 1998 \"Reflectionism' and\n'Diffusionism': New Tactics for Deconstructing the Video Surveillance\nSuperhighway\", in Leonardo, pp. 93â102 \"Sousveillance, Media and\nStrategic Political Communication\", by Dr. Vian Bakir, book ISBN = 978-0-8264-3009-\n0 university course on sousveillance [http://www.ischool.berkeley.edu/courses/290-\nsscd Home âº Courses âº Course Catalog âº 290. Surveillance, Sousveillance,\nCoveillance, and Dataveillance]\n290. SURVEILLANCE, SOUSVEILLANCE, COVEILLANCE, AND\n     DATAVEILLANCE International conferences on sousveillance: [http://www.notanalternative.net/tp-sousveillance-culture-conference-\n     426] and [http://wearcam.org/iwis/] [http://www.wired.com/magazi-\n     ne/2011/06/st_thompson_videomonitoaring/ WiReD magazine], Clive Thompson,\n     \"Establishing Rules in the Videocam Age\", 2011 June 28 [http://www.vancouverobserver.com/GTA/2011/06/28/reflections-\n     vancouver-riots-and-fragility-civilization Reflections on the Vancouver\n     Riots], Vancouver Observer, 2011 June 28\n\nSousveillance has also been described as \"inverse surveillance\", [http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/37560195/#45421629 MSNBC]\nbased on the word surveillance (from the French sur, \"from above\", and veiller,\n\"to watch\"), and substituting the prefix sous, \"from below\".\n\nWhile surveillance and sousveillance both generally refer to visual monitoring,\nthe terms also denote other forms of monitoring such as audio surveillance or\nsousveillance. In the audio sense (e.g. recording of phone conversations)\nsousveillance is referred to as \"one party consent\". [http://www.anonequity-\n.org/weblog/archives/2006/01/exploring_equiv_1.php Exploring Equiveillance,\nUniversity of Ottawa Faculty of Law, Anonequity Project]\n\n'Inverse surveillance' is a subset of sousveillance with a particular emphasis\non the \"watchful vigilance from underneath\" and a form of surveillance inquiry\nor legal protection involving the recording, monitoring, study, or analysis of\nsurveillance systems, proponents of surveillance, and possibly also recordings\nof authority figures and their actions. Inverse surveillance is typically an\nactivity undertaken by those who are generally the subject of surveillance, and\nmay thus be thought of as a form of ethnography or ethnomethodology study (i.e.\nan analysis of the surveilled from the perspective of a participant in a society\nunder surveillance). [http://wearcam.org/sousveillance.pdf\nSousveillance: Inventing and Using Wearable Computing Devices for Data\nCollection in Surveillance Environments, Surveillance & Society 1(3):\n331â355]\n\nSousveillance typically involves community-based recording from first person\nperspectives, without necessarily involving any specific political agenda,\nwhereas inverse-surveillance is a form of sousveillance that is typically\ndirected at, or used to collect data to analyze or study, surveillance or its\nproponents (e.g., the actions of police or protestors at a protest rally).\n","linknr":304,"url":"sousveillance","recorded":1372154260,"links":["